{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-17",
    "title": "The Academic Shift: Present Passive",
    "description": "Introduction to shifting focus from the person to the action or object.",
    "display_order": 17,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-16"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# The Academic Shift: Present Passive\n\nSometimes, we do not care **who** did the action. We care more about **what** was done. This is very common in science and academic writing.\n\n### 1. Active vs. Passive\n- **Active**: The professor **tests** the student. (Focus is on the professor.)\n- **Passive**: The student **is tested** by the professor. (Focus is on the student.)\n\n### 2. How to Make the Present Passive\nUse the **Be Verb** (am / is / are) + the **Past Participle** (V3).\n\n- **Singular**: The report **is written**.\n- **Plural**: The reports **are written**.\n\n### 3. Why use it?\n- **Objectivity**: In science, we often say \"The sample **is heated**\" instead of \"I heat the sample.\"\n- **Unknown Subject**: \"My backpack **is stolen**!\" (I don't know who did it.)\n\n### 4. Common Verbs\n- write \u2192 **written**\n- study \u2192 **studied**\n- use \u2192 **used**\n- show \u2192 **shown**\n- give \u2192 **given**\n\n---",
